SEIR Model with Social Distancing on Maharashta Covid-19 Data

Parts of code taken from Tim Churches blog on “Analysing COVID-19 (2019-nCoV) outbreak data with R” https://timchurches.github.io/blog/posts/2020-02-18-analysing-covid-19-2019-ncov-outbreak-data-with-r-part-1/

Maharashtra Data from: https://github.com/covid19india/api

SEIR Model with social distancing from: https://aalexan3.math.ncsu.edu/articles/covid_control.pdf

Here, I will try to fit the SEIR(Susceptible, Exposed, Infected, Recovered) model with social distancing incorporated to Maharashtra Covid-19 data. u denotes level of social distancing, u=0 means no social distancing and u=1 means full lockdown.
In a closed population (that is, assuming no births or deaths), the SEIR model with social distancing incorporated is:

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dS}{dt} & = -\frac{(1-u)\beta IS}{N}\\ \\ \frac{dE}{dt} & = \frac{(1-u)\beta IS}{N} - \kappa E\\ \\ \frac{dI}{dt} & = \kappa E - \gamma I\\ \\ \frac{dR}{dt} & = \gamma I \end{aligned} \]

The dat DataFrame has all states data. Filter Maharashtra Data and get the daily Confirmed, Recovered, Deceased cases of Maharashtra along with dates. Put these data in new DataFrame mh_dat.

Confirmed <- dat %>% filter(status == "Confirmed") %>% pull(mh)
Confirmed <- as.numeric(Confirmed)
Recovered <- dat %>% filter(status == "Recovered") %>% pull(mh)
Recovered <- as.numeric(Recovered)
Deceased <- dat %>% filter(status == "Deceased") %>% pull(mh)
Deceased <- as.numeric(Deceased)
Date <- dat %>% filter(status == "Confirmed") %>% pull(date)
Short_date <- dat %>% filter(status == "Confirmed") %>% pull(short_date)

mh_dat <- data.frame("Confirmed" = Confirmed, "Recovered" = Recovered, "Deceased" = Deceased, 
                     "Date" = Date, "Short_date"=Short_date)

For SEIR model we need cumulative daily confirmed cases and not daily confirmed cases. Get the cumulative confirmed, Recovered and, Deceased cases and then subtract cumulative recovered and cumulative deceased cases from cumulative confirmed cases to get actual cumulative confirmed cases for each day.

mh_dat <- within(mh_dat, Cum_Confirmed <- cumsum(Confirmed))
mh_dat <- within(mh_dat, Cum_Recovered <- cumsum(Recovered))
mh_dat <- within(mh_dat, Cum_Deceased <- cumsum(Deceased))

mh_dat$Cum_Confirmed = mh_dat$Cum_Confirmed - (mh_dat$Cum_Recovered + mh_dat$Cum_Deceased)

Express the differential equations of SEIR model with social distancing as an R function.Full lockdown is impossible, as some people will have to be out for maintaining essential services. By associating cost with social distancing optimal value of u found was 0.6031.
Source: https://aalexan3.math.ncsu.edu/articles/covid_control.pdf

SEIR <- function(time, state, parameters) {
  par <- as.list(c(state, parameters))
  with(par, {
    dS <- -(1-0.6031)*beta * I * S/N
    dE <- (1-0.6071)*beta * I * S/N - kappa * E
    dI <- kappa * E - gamma * I
    dR <- gamma * I
    list(c(dS, dE, dI, dR))
  })
}

Nation wide lockdown started on 25th March. So, consider the cumulative infected/confirmed cases from 25th March 2020 till 30th April 2020 for finding optimal values of model paramters

Infected <- mh_dat %>% filter(Date >= dmy("25-Mar-20"), Date <= dmy("30-Apr-20")) %>% 
  pull(Cum_Confirmed)

Create an incrementing Day vector the same length as Infected. Initialize N with a population of Maharashtra. Initially, everyone is in susceptible class, so initialize Susceptible with S = N - cumulative confirmed cases on 25th march(First day of data), Infected (I) with cumulative Infected cases on 25th March, Exposed (E) with twice of Infected cases, recovered R = 1 from the data.

Day <- 1:(length(Infected))
N <- 114200000
init <- c(S = N - Infected[1], E=Infected[1]*2, I = Infected[1], R = 1)

Define a function RSS(Residual Sum of Squares) which needs to be minimized for Infected and predicted Infected cases to get optimum value for parameters β, γ, κ of differential equations.

RSS <- function(parameters) {
  names(parameters) <- c("beta", "kappa", "gamma")
  out <- ode(y = init, times = Day, func = SEIR, parms = parameters)
  fit <- out[, 4]
  sum((Infected - fit)^2)
}

Fit the SEIR model to our data by finding the values for β, γ, κ that minimize the residual sum of squares between the observed cumulative infected cases and the predicted cumulative infected cases. We are already in community transmission so set limit beta to be high. In India recovery is good, so set gamma’s lower limit as 0.622(found by trial and error on curve)

Opt <- optim(c(0.5, 0.5, 0.5), RSS, method = "L-BFGS-B", lower = c(0, 0, 0.622), upper = c(2, 1, 1))
Opt$message
## [1] "CONVERGENCE: NORM OF PROJECTED GRADIENT <= PGTOL"

Get the parameter values and set the names of parameters

Opt_par <- setNames(Opt$par, c("beta", "kappa", "gamma"))
Opt_par
##  beta kappa gamma 
## 2.000 1.000 0.622

Let’s use this model to predict the cumulative infected cases until 14th May.

t <- 1:as.integer(dmy("14-May-20") - dmy("25-Mar-20"))
fitted_cumulative_incidence <- data.frame(ode(y = init, times = t, func = SEIR, parms = Opt_par))

fitted_cumulative_incidence <- fitted_cumulative_incidence %>% 
  mutate(Date = dmy("25-Mar-20") + days(t - 1)) %>% 
  left_join(mh_dat %>% ungroup() %>% select(Date, Cum_Confirmed))
## Joining, by = "Date"
fitted_cumulative_incidence %>% filter(Date <= dmy("14-May-2020")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date)) + geom_line(aes(y = I), colour = "red") + 
  geom_point(aes(y = Cum_Confirmed), colour = "orange") + 
  labs(y = "Cumulative Infected", 
       title = "COVID-19 fitted vs actual cumulative infected, Maharashtra", 
       subtitle = "(red=fitted infected from SEIR model, orange=actual cumulative infected)")

We can see that the actual infected is very close to predicted infected cases because of inclusion of social distancing. Let’s see what will happen if the outbreak is left to run under these conditions that is with around 60% lockdown.

t <- 1:180
fitted_cumulative_incidence <- data.frame(ode(y = init, times = t, 
                                              func = SEIR, parms = Opt_par))

fitted_cumulative_incidence <- fitted_cumulative_incidence %>% 
  mutate(Date = dmy("25-Mar-20") + days(t - 1)) %>% 
  left_join(mh_dat %>% ungroup() %>% select(Date, Cum_Confirmed))
## Joining, by = "Date"
fitted_cumulative_incidence %>% ggplot(aes(x = Date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = I), colour = "red") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = S), colour = "black") +

       subtitle = "(black=susceptible cases, brown=exposed cases, red=infected cases, 
       green=recovered cases, orange points = actual cumulative infected cases till date.)")

We see that number of infected is much less because of lockdown with peak around mid July. Epidemic is likely to end around mid August.
